String vs String Builder in depth

String is immutable, once created it cannot be changed. Any modification creates a new String object.

String Constant Pool
- Where we store the objects of String literals.
means String s1 = "Hello"; // stored in String constant pool
String s2 = "Hello"; // s2 will point to the same object in the String constant pool

Hello <- points by s1 and s2

if we use new keyword then it will create a new object in heap memory
String s3 = new String("Hello"); // creates a new object in heap memory 
String s4 = new String("Hello"); // creates another new object in heap memory

Thread Safety
No synchronization needed

String Pool Optimization
Reuse objects → memory efficient
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
StringBuilder - it is mutable, can be modified after creation. It is not thread-safe, so it should be used in single-threaded environments.

StringBuilder:
[ h e l l o _ _ _ _ ]
           ↑ capacity

Uses char[] array
Has:
capacity
length

Default:
capacity = 16

When exceeded:
new capacity = (old * 2) + 2

